## Phase 3: QuickPose Assessment Pipeline (iOS)

> **Goal:** The client can run a guided movement capture session using QuickPose on their iPhone. The app computes ROM, joint angles, asymmetry, and movement quality on-device and uploads a structured assessment to the backend.
> **Owner:** iOS agent
> **Estimated time:** 4вҖ“6 hours (largest phase for iOS)
> **Dependencies:** Phase 0 (QuickPose SDK installed), Phase 1 (auth)
> **Judging impact:** Practitioner Impact (25pts), Technical Feasibility (20pts), UX (15pts)

### 3.1 Guided Capture Flow

The client performs a sequence of guided movements. Each movement targets specific body regions and captures specific metrics.

**Default assessment sequence (configurable by practitioner):**

| # | Movement | Duration | Targets | Metrics captured |
|---|----------|----------|---------|-----------------|
| 1 | Standing front view | 5 seconds | Full body baseline | Posture, shoulder level, hip level, knee alignment |
| 2 | Standing side view | 5 seconds | Spinal alignment | Forward head posture, thoracic curve, lumbar curve |
| 3 | Shoulder flexion (both arms) | 10 seconds | Shoulders | Shoulder ROM, bilateral asymmetry |
| 4 | Squat | 10 seconds | Hips, knees, ankles | Squat depth, knee tracking, trunk lean, ankle mobility |
| 5 | Hip hinge | 8 seconds | Lower back, hips | Hamstring flexibility, hip ROM, lumbar flexion |
| 6 | Single-leg balance (R) | 10 seconds | Right leg, core | Stability, ankle wobble, compensation |
| 7 | Single-leg balance (L) | 10 seconds | Left leg, core | Stability, asymmetry vs right |

**Total capture time: ~58 seconds** (under the 60-second clinic-compatible constraint)

