## Appendix D: Judging Rubric & Scoring Strategy

### D.1 Rubric (100 base + 18 bonus = 118 max)

| Criterion | Points | HydraScan coverage |
|-----------|--------|-------------------|
| Practitioner Impact | 25 | Recovery Map (60-second understanding), protocol recommendation (< 2 min), outcome visibility |
| Technical Feasibility | 20 | QuickPose on-device, Supabase backend, real MQTT API integration, typed schemas |
| Platform Integration | 20 | JWT auth, MQTT publish, SessionConfig matches API schema, device targeting by MAC |
| Path to Product | 20 | Multi-tenant auth, RLS, safe envelope, learning loop, production repo structure |
| User Experience | 15 | < 60 sec intake, guided capture, clean practitioner console, Recovery Score |
| **BONUS: Loop Coverage** | **+10** | Assessment (Know) + Session (Act) + Outcomes (Learn) = full loop |
| **BONUS: Live Data Demo** | **+5** | Real device session launch via MQTT API (or clearly badged simulation) |
| **BONUS: Business Model** | **+3** | Per-session pricing, ROI calculator, retention metric |

### D.2 Scoring Strategy

- **Prioritize Practitioner Impact (25pts):** The Recovery Map must be the star of the demo. If one thing works perfectly, it should be this.
- **Ensure Platform Integration (20pts):** The MQTT API integration must be visible in the demo вҖ” show the payload, show the MAC address, show the API response.
- **Chase the Loop Coverage bonus (+10pts):** This is the highest-value bonus. Show all three stages clearly.
- **The Live Data Demo bonus (+5pts) is the most impressive differentiator.** If you can launch a session on a real device during the demo, that will be memorable.

